Writing the four formats.

Writing mirrors reading exactly. You take a dataframe, choose a mode, name a format, and save to a path. The same four formats are available on the way out as on the way in — csv, json, parquet, and orc.

The one detail to notice is that Spark does not write a single file. It writes a directory full of part files, one part per partition of the dataframe. So when you write a csv, you get a folder named like a file, with several part files inside it, plus a small success marker. That surprises people coming from pandas, where a write produces one neat file.

The format you pick on write should match how the data will be read. If it feeds analytics, write parquet — columnar, compressed, and fast to scan. If a human or an external tool needs to open it, csv or json is friendlier even though it is larger and slower.

To keep examples repeatable, it is common to write with overwrite mode, so re-running the same code does not pile up duplicate output.
